How to finance the green transition
NEW YORK – This week, world leaders have gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global war on climate change and submit new pledges for emissions reductions.
The climate crisis is a matter of great urgency, and our actions are far too slow.
We are unable to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Fortunately, private-sector cooperation to address climate change is on the rise thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI).
Under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Climate Ambition Special Envoy, the CFLI was established with the purpose of mobilizing private capital at the global level to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled Financing the Low Carbon Future, which outlines how to expand green finance to support an orderly transition to a low-carbon economy and identifies opportunities for public-private cooperation to achieve the Paris Climate Agreement targets for 2015.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, responding to the call of the leaders of Europe’s nations and the newly elected President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen, we are prepared to step up our ambition and reinforce the EIB’s role as a specialized climate bank for the EU.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and commit to investing at least 1 trillion euros over the next decade for low-carbon projects.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of the EIB financing will be allocated to climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Accord.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to low-carbon futures.
As an EU bank, our task is to invest in Europe's future, and the most pressing issue among these is undoubtedly climate change.
How urgent the climate crisis is, the stronger our resolve will be.
Just this summer, Europe suffered from record-high temperatures and crop failures, due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries also have similar experiences.
Floods and other phenomena caused by climate patterns cost major cities billions of dollars annually and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as funding for new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues many of the world’s cities.
Changing investment models could accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels, which has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, while a majority of U.S. coal-fired power plants retired, the clean energy sector created 3.3 million jobs, whereas the coal industry had fewer than 100,000.
Moreover, an increasing number of American cities and states are committing to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will benefit from the support of Beyond Carbon, a initiative launched by the Bloomberg Philanthropies last year with the aim of fully decarbonizing the US economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce our investment in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially still paying for climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investment towards electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive transformative changes toward a green transition.
These investments will yield huge returns, including reducing the significant cost to public health caused by air pollution.
Besides this, we can also take numerous measures to guide necessary funding.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors have had no clue about climate-related risks, unaware of the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies in more sustainable ways of allocating capital, and enabling investors to reward those that seriously address climate change.
Secondly, we must clarify the investment risks associated with green finance.
Cities contribute more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few cities in the developing world are able to obtain credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transportation, energy-efficient buildings, and other projects aimed at reducing emissions has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including by joining the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led with Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to achieve modernization of the power grid.
Refunds and tax incentives, among other incentives, promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for both businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar initiatives to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, thereby speeding up our efforts to overcome intermittency issues.
Furthermore, better grid connectivity could enable regions with surpluses of wind and solar power to supply regions with shortages.
The government can play a leadership role in these two areas by encouraging more private investment to flow into clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
But compared to a global bond market valued at $100 trillion, this is merely a drop in the bucket.
Thus, the EIB is helping the EU develop a sustainable finance taxonomy so that investors can compare similar projects, much like standard bonds.
Better and more information about investment carbon footprints would enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment into low-carbon projects.
This is how we finance the green transition.
